s and examines the thorny scientific, philosophical, and ethical questions it raises. Once we accept that animals dream, we incur a host of moral obligations and have no choice but to rethink our views about who animals are and the interior lives they lead.A mesmerizing journey into the otherworldly domain of nonhuman consciousness, When Animals Dream carries profound implications for contemporary debates about animal cognition, animal ethics, and animal rights, challenging us to regard animals as beings who matter, and for whom things matter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAnimal rightsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aConsciousness in animals. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAbductive reasoning.  aActivation.  aAffair.  aAlgorithm.  aAmerican Psychological Association.  aAmmunition.  aAmygdala.  aAnimal Dreams.  aAnimal cognition.  aAnimal consciousness.  aAnimal rights.  aAugustine of Hippo.  aBDSM.  aBehavior.  aBessel van der Kolk.  aBioethics.  aBody schema.  aBoris Cyrulnik.  aBrainstem.  aChimpanzee.  aCognition.  aCognitive map.  aConcept learning.  aConsciousness.  aDan Zahavi.  aDaydream.  aDelusion.  aDescartes' Error.  aDiaphragmatic breathing.  aDisinhibition.  aDorsolateral prefrontal cortex.  aDream world (plot device).  aEdmund Husserl.  aElaboration.  aEmotion.  aEmpathy.  aEpilogue.  aExistence.  aExistentialism.  aExplanation.  aFacial expression.  aFacial muscles.  aFeeling.  aGaston Bachelard.  aHallucination.  aHeat exhaustion.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aHuman science.  aImagination.  aInsomnia.  aInstance (computer science).  aIntentionality.  aIpso facto.  aIsolation tank.  aJean-Paul Sartre.  aJohn Searle.  aJohn Stuart Mill.  aKantianism.  aLucid dream.  